  <article>
    <h1>Splints I Use in Retraining</h1>
    <p>Splinting is a physical method used to temporarily restrict the movement of adjacent fingers. Because focal hand dystonia involves co-contraction and neural overlap, restricting non-affected fingers helps isolate the neural signals to the target finger.</p>
    
    <p>The splints I construct and recommend are lightweight, custom-fitted, and non-painful. They serve as an educational guide for the motor cortex, showing the brain how to move one finger without causing others to collapse or curl.</p>

    <blockquote>
      "By physically preventing co-contraction, a splint allows the brain to map pure, isolated movement signals once again."
    </blockquote>
    
